import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import zscore

# Extract numerical features (excluding 'Time', 'Amount', and 'Class')
numerical_features = cdt.drop(['Time', 'Amount', 'Class'], axis=1)

# Calculate Z-scores for each numerical feature
z_scores = zscore(numerical_features)

# Set a Z-score threshold
z_score_threshold = 3

# Identify and handle outliers by removing or transforming them
outliers = (abs(z_scores) > z_score_threshold).any(axis=1)
cdt_no_outliers = cdt[~outliers]

# Check the shape of the resulting DataFrame after handling outliers
print("Shape before handling outliers:", df.shape)
print("Shape after handling outliers:", cdt_no_outliers.shape)
print(f"Number of outliers removed: {sum(outliers)}")

3. Train a logistic regression model as a baseline model.¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline

# Extract features and labels
X, y = cdt_no_outliers.drop('Class', axis=1), cdt_no_outliers['Class']

# Combine preprocessing and model into a pipeline for Logistic Regression
logistic_model = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), LogisticRegression())

# Use 5-fold cross-validation for Logistic Regression
cv = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
logistic_cross_val_results = cross_val_score(logistic_model, X, y, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy')

# Print the cross-validation results for Logistic Regression
print("Logistic Regression Cross-Validation Results:")
print(logistic_cross_val_results)
print(f"Average Accuracy: {logistic_cross_val_results.mean()}")

4. Print the coefficients of the logistic regression model. Comment on which feature the model gave higher weight to.¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline

# Inspect the columns of the dataset to ensure 'Class' exists
print(cdt_no_outliers.columns)

# Check if 'Class' exists in the dataset
if 'Class' in cdt_no_outliers.columns:
    # Extract features and labels
    X, y = cdt_no_outliers.drop('Class', axis=1), cdt_no_outliers['Class']

    # Combine preprocessing and model into a pipeline
    model = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), LogisticRegression())

    # Fit the model on the entire dataset
    model.fit(X, y)

    # Get the learned coefficients
    coefficients = model.named_steps['logisticregression'].coef_[0]

    # Pair feature names with coefficients and print
    feature_coefficients = list(zip(X.columns, coefficients))
    for feature, coefficient in feature_coefficients:
        print(f"{feature}: {coefficient}")

    # Identify the feature with the highest weight
    max_feature = max(feature_coefficients, key=lambda x: abs(x[1]))
    print(f"\nFeature with the highest weight: {max_feature[0]} (Weight: {max_feature[1]})")
else:
    print("'Class' not found in the dataset.")

X_test, y_test = cdt_no_outliers.drop('Class', axis=1), cdt_no_outliers['Class']

6. Plot the ROC Curve and print the AUC of the model on the test set. Comment on the quality of the model performance as seen in the ROC curve.¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Get predicted probabilities for the positive class
y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Calculate ROC curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)

# Calculate AUC
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

# Plot ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label=f'AUC = {roc_auc:.4f}')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

# Print AUC
print(f"AUC: {roc_auc:.4f}")

AUC: 0.5826

An AUC around 0.5 indicates that the model's ability to discriminate between fraud and non-fraud transactions is not much better.The ROC curve may show that the model struggles to balance sensitivity (true positive rate) and specificity (true negative rate). The current logistic regression model may not be highly effective in distinguishing between fraud and non-fraud transactions¶
